  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Pricing a property is often framed as a financial exercise. Work out the comparable sales, add a bit for presentation, subtract a bit for the market, land on a number. That framing misses most of what actually drives the result. For the buyers looking at your home online, the asking price is not a neutral piece of information. It is an anchor, and it shapes every judgment they make about the property from that point forward.</p>

      <p>Anchoring is one of the most robustly demonstrated effects in behavioural economics. People rely heavily on the first piece of information they receive when making subsequent decisions, even when that first piece is arbitrary. In property, the first price a buyer sees becomes the reference point against which every later number is compared. Their willingness to pay, their sense of what is reasonable, and their emotional response to negotiation are all shaped by that initial anchor. Sellers who understand this price their campaigns very differently to sellers who do not.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The asking price as anchor</h2>
      <p>Imagine two identical Morningside homes, both genuinely worth $1.1 million. One is listed at $1.2 million. The other is listed at $1.1 million. In the $1.2 million campaign, buyers form an internal reference point around $1.2 million. When they make offers, those offers cluster in the $1.08 million to $1.15 million range, because buyers feel they are negotiating against $1.2 million, not against $1.1 million. In the $1.1 million campaign, buyers anchor at $1.1 million, and offers may come in slightly below because they feel the asking price is the ceiling.</p>

      <p>This is why a realistic asking price, set slightly above what the seller expects to receive, often produces a stronger result than a price pitched exactly at market value. The premium needs to be genuine, not aspirational. A $50,000 premium on a $1.1 million home is credible. A $200,000 premium is not, and it triggers a different problem altogether.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The too-high-anchor trap</h2>
      <p>An asking price significantly above realistic market value does not just produce lower offers. It produces no offers, because serious buyers filter the property out before they even inspect it. A buyer browsing realestate.com.au with a $1.1 million budget sets their filter at $1.2 million maximum. A property priced at $1.3 million never appears in their search. The property with the inflated price loses the most motivated portion of its buyer pool on day one.</p>

      <p>Inquiry volume is the clearest early signal. A correctly priced home in Brisbane's inner east typically generates 30 to 60 online inquiries and 15 to 30 inspection bookings in the first two weeks. An overpriced home often generates fewer than 10 inquiries and a handful of inspections, most of them curious neighbours rather than committed buyers. By week three, the campaign is starved of the data it needs (real buyer feedback, competitive tension, pressure to decide) and the agent is reduced to guessing at what the market thinks.</p>

      <p>Days on market is the secondary signal. Once a property has been listed for six or eight weeks without selling, buyers start asking what is wrong with it. The stigma of extended time on market is genuine, and it grows the longer the listing sits. By the time the price is adjusted, the remaining buyer pool has shrunk and the ones still watching know the seller is under pressure. That is the opposite of the position a seller wants to be negotiating from.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the research actually shows</h2>
      <p>Studies of listing behaviour across comparable markets consistently find the same pattern. Properties listed at or very slightly above realistic market value attract more inquiries, more inspections, and stronger offers than properties listed 10 per cent or more above market. The mechanism is simple: accurate pricing keeps the property inside buyer search filters, generates competitive tension in the first two weeks (when buyer interest is highest), and avoids the stigma that attaches to long-running listings.</p>

      <p>The counterintuitive finding for sellers is that trying to leave negotiating room by pitching high typically produces a worse result, not a better one. The room you think you are creating is filled by buyers who never inspect, and the negotiating leverage you think you are preserving is erased by extended time on market. A well-prepared, accurately priced campaign consistently outperforms an overpriced one at the same property.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The price guide in an auction campaign</h2>
      <p>For auction campaigns, the price guide performs the anchoring function the asking price plays in a private-treaty sale. Buyers use the guide to decide whether to attend, what their bidding ceiling should be, and how competitive the auction is likely to be. A realistic price guide attracts committed bidders who are prepared to transact near that level. A deliberately low guide attracts a different pool altogether, buyers whose budgets sit below the seller's actual expectation, and the campaign either produces a passed-in result or a difficult renegotiation.</p>

      <p>Queensland has strict rules against underquoting. A price guide that is materially below the agent's reasonable expectation of the likely result can breach the Property Occupations Act. Setting the guide accurately is both a legal obligation and a campaign strategy choice that determines who shows up on auction day.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Psychological price thresholds</h2>
      <p>Round numbers matter more than sellers usually realise, because the property portals are organised around them. A buyer searching realestate.com.au for homes under $1 million sees properties listed up to $999,999, plus a fraction of properties listed at exactly $1 million, depending on how the filter is implemented. A property listed at $1,000,000 is often invisible to that search entirely. A property listed at $999,000 captures buyers from both the 'under $1 million' cohort and the 'under $1.1 million' cohort.</p>

      <p>The same effect applies at other thresholds: $800,000, $900,000, $1.2 million, $1.5 million. Sellers whose realistic result sits just above a threshold should look hard at whether pricing $1,000 below the threshold would materially increase inquiry volume. Sometimes the answer is obvious. A home worth $1.02 million priced at $999,000 is giving away money. A home worth $1.005 million priced at $999,000 is probably catching a larger buyer pool at minimal cost. The right call depends on where your expected result actually sits.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The 'priced to sell' signal</h2>
      <p>An asking price set $10,000 to $20,000 below realistic market value sends a specific signal: the seller wants to transact quickly. Buyers who see the signal respond with urgency, which can produce multiple offers above the asking price and a fast campaign result. This is sometimes the right strategy, particularly when the seller has a firm deadline (simultaneous purchase, relocation, estate settlement) and is happy to trade a small amount of price upside for speed and certainty.</p>

      <p>It is not the right strategy in most campaigns. A 'priced to sell' asking price used without a genuine reason leaves money on the table, because the urgency it creates is buyer urgency, not a premium over market. Use the signal deliberately when speed is a genuine priority. Do not use it as a default.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Price reductions during a campaign</h2>
      <p>When a campaign is not producing inquiries or offers, a price reduction is often the right response. The size of the reduction matters as much as the decision to reduce. A meaningful reduction resets the anchor: buyers compare the new price to the old, register that the seller is serious, and re-evaluate whether the property is now worth inspecting. A cosmetic reduction does none of that. It signals to the market that the seller is testing a lower number rather than committing to one.</p>

      <p>A $5,000 reduction on a $1,150,000 campaign is cosmetic. A $50,000 reduction on the same campaign is meaningful. The threshold depends on the price point, but the rule of thumb is that a reduction needs to be around 3 to 5 per cent of the asking price to materially shift buyer perception. Reductions below that level tend to extend the campaign without generating new interest, which compounds the days-on-market problem rather than solving it.</p>

      <p>Related reading on adjusting price mid-campaign is covered in our guide on when to reduce asking price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The competitive context</h2>
      <p>Buyers never judge your asking price in isolation. They judge it against the other listings they are seeing in the same week, in the same suburb, at the same price point. If three comparable homes in Morningside are priced at $1.05 million and yours is priced at $1.15 million, your $100,000 premium has to be visibly justified: bigger land, better aspect, better renovation, superior school catchment. Without that visible justification, the buyer's anchor resets to the competing listings and your home looks overpriced by comparison.</p>

      <p>The competitive context is not static. A property that was realistically priced when it launched can look overpriced six weeks later if three cheaper, comparable homes have come on to the market since. Sellers and their agents need to watch the comparable listings that appear during the campaign, not just the sales that happened before it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should actually do</h2>
      <p>Price at or just above realistic market value for a private-treaty campaign, using a premium of 3 to 5 per cent rather than 10 to 15. Use a price guide for an auction campaign that genuinely reflects the expected result, not a headline that will collapse under scrutiny. Pay attention to round-number thresholds when your expected result sits close to one, and decide deliberately whether to price just under or just over. Use 'priced to sell' signals only when speed is genuinely more important than maximising the result. If the campaign needs a price reduction, make it meaningful enough to reset the anchor.</p>

      <p>Pricing a property is as much a psychological exercise as a financial one. The buyer's perception of the price relative to their anchor drives their response. Get the anchor right and the rest of the campaign works with you. Get it wrong and every subsequent decision (inquiries, inspections, offers, eventual result) becomes damage control.</p>

